old.desc:
This is a set of resources you should be familiar with. It is the face of our company, the main ways in wich we communicate with the outside world.
Your perspective is unique qnd precious! You are new to CrateDB so you can really feel what our prospects go through when they start learning about CrateDB. If your experience is not great, if something is not clear or it could be done better, you are in the perfect place to contribute and make this better.
Just remember there is always the risk of "boiling the ocean": before thinking about revolutioning the world in a way that would be not applicable, try to think on how you can make this better, and start contributing!
This will make your job as TSS much easier, because people will come your way already informed about what we do, so it will only be a matter of clarifying their particular implementation or requirements .

cards.desc:
Pingboard is the tool Crate.io uses to give colleagues an overview of the org chart and it also gives an overview of people's whereabouts. 

👍: Make sure your availability is always up to date. It is important to know when you are in the office / available / remote.

📄 Besides make sure you add a short bio about yourself and skills so your colleagues know for which areas they can contact you.

👀 Have a look at [Sarah's profile](https://crate.pingboard.com/users/444009), it is very neat.

It is also a great starting point to get orientation about:

* where is my place in the organisation?
* who is located where?
* who has what role at Crate.io?
* is someone on holidays / out of office / in home office / sick?
* what was the phone number of my colleague again which I wanted to invite for a drink? 🍸
cards.name: Update your pingboard profile with your personal information ℹ️

cards.desc:
**If you are based in Dornbirn:** Usually every Monday we cook for all our coworkers in our office in Dornbirn. Be one of the chefs and make your colleagues happy with your cooking skills. 

**If you are based in Berlin, Munich or New York:** Join the team lunch and tell a fun joke to break the ice. Maybe you want to have some 🍨 afterwards 😋

**If you are based somewhere remote:** Make sure you make you book to visit the team in Dornbirn or Berlin for a week as part of the onboarding procedure. Be one of the chefs and make your colleagues happy with your cooking skills.

cards.desc:
Go to https://firewall.bregenz.a1.cr8.net/ and log in with your account. If you don't have the credentials ask your team companion or the engineering scrum master for advice.

Authenticate with 2xfactor authentication and OTP in order to login. This means you need a authenticator app on your mobile.

**Take care it you need to type in your password + the number which is created by the authenticator.**

Download your preferred desktop client to administer your VPN access (we usually use Tunnelblick). There you only need to login with your credentials (this time without the authenticator app).

cards.desc:
It is the domain leads' responsibility to sit down with the new hire and define some bilateral expectations on the personal development. @domainlead assign yourself and the new hire to this card. Some guidelines:

1. Make the expectations clear to yourself (domain lead)
2. Know where you need expectations (domain lead)
3. Understand why the expectations are important (domain lead)
4. Meet and discuss with the new hire (domain lead and new hire)
5. Make it mutual (domain lead and new hire)
6. Write them down (domain lead and new hire)
7. Get an agreement and commitment (domain lead and new hire)

👍: Consider the areas methodical skills, self and social skills, professional expertise and culture fit. Think about on which level the skills of the role of the new hire has to be.

👍: **Use a Google Doc** to keep track of the expectations. Make sure this is confidential since employee files are sensitive data.

Source: [Seven steps to setting clear expectations](https://blog.kevineikenberry.com/leadership-supervisory-skills/seven-steps-to-setting-clear-expectations/)
cards.name: Set expectations ☑️

cards.desc:

Of course you can [read them](https://intranet.crate.io/handbook/values/index.html) anytime in our handbook. However, for more background and deeper understanding go through it with your domain lead. They are happy to share their story. 📖

checkItems.name: Give the team a clear description of what function the person will have.
Figure out where the person will sit and on what the person will work in the first weeks.
Ask the new hire for a short introduction and photo which is also suitable for the website.
Introduce the new hire beforehand with an introduction via mail to the whole team.

Be clear on what time the new hire should be in the office on the first day. Best practice is 10am. This is good for Crate to finish any outstanding tasks and for the new hire to start with loaded batteries.
If the new hire needs business cards make sure you [order them upfront on Moo](https://www.moo.com/m4b/account/signup/landing/1800f133-715e-4b58-a257-f825b0804f67).
Make your the new employee is not overloaded with meetings in the first week. Give them space to process information and breathe between the meetings.
First week review - this one is easy going and not too structured. Ask how the first week was and if something is missing.
Check-in with the new hire on a daily basis during the first week therefor suggest a time before the new hire starts. If you need to adjust it, clarify it on the first day.
Have regular weekly 1:1 meetings with the new hire to catch up.
Group lists for access and mail distribution
Drink (only if the goodie bag is not sent)
Handwritten personal note from the domain lead
Ask for deep dive introductions any time
[Company vision and mission](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1cn3nuXueAKca2kNMsoThm2O9qfNJkicrA9DuqzmKd84/edit#slide=id.p): what guides us into the future?

**Shadow a Qualification call**: This is usually done when a prospect reached the MQL status, we'll ask basic questions to make sure there are the basis for an opportunity or not
**Shadow a first call with Prospect**: after the MQL get through the first filter, a Sales rep would have a first call with the prospect to ask the **10% questions**
**Shadow a POC scoping call with Dominik M.** : this will give you insight on what are the important informations we need to go into an actual POC implementation

**Shadow an onsite meeting with Christian / Jodok B.**: it is important for you to understand how we interact with higher level executives (C*O), Christian and Jodok run such meetings with key stakeholders of prospects
